<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
57. 
<taxonomicName LSID="EAC493EF-74AA-5A57-82E6-9DC15954154D" authority="R. W. Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson 2001: 12)." authorityName="R. W. Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson" authorityYear="2001" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus graminetinus" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="graminetinus">Convolvulus graminetinus R.W.Johnson, Austrobaileya 6: 12. 2001. (Johnson 2001: 12).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
AUSTRALIA, Queensland, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">R.W.Johnson</emphasis>
5300 (holotype BRI; isotypes CANB, K!, NE, NSW).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Perennial herb with trailing or twining stems to at least 50 cm, plant thinly pubescent to glabrescent. Leaves petiolate, dimorphic; petioles 2-10 mm; lowermost leaves 2.5-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.6-1.6 cm, deltoid, obtuse and finely mucronate, entire, base truncate and briefly cuneate onto the petiole, auricles absent; middle leaves similar but base more or less cordate, auricles present, often bifid or tridentate, the central lobe longer and narrower; middle and upper leaves with a narrowly linear-lanceolate central lobe 3-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.1-0. 6 cm, the basal auricles more or less reflexed so base sagittate, inconspicuous, bifid or trifid, 3-5 mm long, segments usually very narrow. Flowers solitary (very rarely paired), pedunculate, axillary; peduncles 1.2-3.5(-5.5) cm, recurved in fruit; bracteoles 1-2.5 mm, filiform; pedicels 4-12 mm; sepals 4-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3 mm, obovate or elliptic, rounded and mucronate, scarious-margined, glabrous or pubescent on dorsal surface near apex; corolla 0.7-1.6 cm long, pink, shallowly lobed with triangular lobes, midpetaline bands pilose; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 3-4 mm above base, stigmas 1.5-2 mm. Capsule glabrous; seeds with prominent wavy tubercles. [
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, RW" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="1 - 39" refId="B167" refString="Johnson, RW, 2001. A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia. Austrobaileya 6: 1 - 39" title="A taxonomic revision of Convolvulus L. (Convolvulaceae) in Australia." volume="6" year="2001">Johnson 2001</bibRefCitation>
: 12-14, figs3-4, map 2]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Australia: Northern Territory, Queensland and New South Wales (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Evans</emphasis>
3248, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Must</emphasis>
1510, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Johnson</emphasis>
2075, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Hubbard</emphasis>
3171, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">McDonald</emphasis>
46, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Clemens</emphasis>
s.n. [9/1945], 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">McBarron</emphasis>
14875, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Melville</emphasis>
3425). Reported from New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation author="Heenan, PB" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="204" pageNumber="205" pagination="447 - 457" publicationUrl="10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" refId="B151" refString="Heenan, PB, Molloy, BPJ, de Lange, PJ, 2003. Species of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae)- endemic to New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Botany 41: 447 - 457, DOI: 10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" title="Species of Convolvulus (Convolvulaceae) - endemic to New Zealand." url="10.1080/0028825X.2003.9512862" volume="41" year="2003">Heenan et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
) but possibly extinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="97" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="96" pageNumber="97">
Very immature plants could be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the corolla is much smaller. More mature plants without lower leaves are similar morphologically to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Br., Prodr. Fl. Nov. Holland 483. 1810. (Brown" authorityYear="1810" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus remotus" order="Solanales" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="96" pageNumber="97">Convolvulus remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the fruiting peduncle is recurved. The strongly tuberculate seeds and the leaves with a very long narrow central lobe combined with the small bifid auricles are also rather distinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
